	directAnswerHtml={`<strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">If you are Jewish, the God your own Scriptures reveal already calls Himself your Father.</strong> The covenant is yours, the prophets are yours, the Psalms are yours — and within them, again and again, the Holy One is named as Father. "You, O LORD, are our Father" (Isaiah 64:8). "As a father has compassion on his children, so the LORD has compassion on those who fear Him" (Psalm 103:13). Whether you searched "God as Father in the Hebrew Bible," "does God love His people," or "Bible verses about God's fatherly love," the answer is already written in the Tanakh. The <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Father's Heart Bible™</a> is a fresh English translation, free to read and <em>listen to</em>, that simply makes visible the Father-heart of God your own Scriptures already proclaim — not to replace what you treasure, but to honor the intimacy your prophets sang of.`}
	keyTakeaway={`The God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob reveals Himself as Father in your own Scriptures — He longs to be known not only as Sovereign and Lawgiver, but as a Father who loves His children with everlasting compassion.`}
	painsHeading={`A God of awe — and of tender compassion`}
	painsIntroHtml={`The God of Israel is rightly held in awe — transcendent, holy, beyond all naming. And yet the same Scriptures that command reverence also sing of His Fatherly tenderness. For many today, that nearness can feel distant. The numbers tell part of the story.`}
