	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Behind every figure is a person and a people with a story unlike any other — a people who carried the Scriptures of the living God across millennia, through exile and return, through unspeakable suffering, through faithfulness that the world owes a debt of gratitude to. To be Jewish is to belong to the covenant people, the people of Torah, of awe, of remembrance and tradition.</p><p>And within that very heritage there is a tenderness sometimes easy to lose beneath the weight of law and transcendence. The Holy One is approached with reverence — rightly so — yet your own prophets insist He is also near: a Father who carries His child, who has compassion, who longs to be known intimately. For some, faith has grown distant or has become more cultural than personal; for others, the ache is simply to feel close to a God who can seem far above. The good news is older than any of us: the nearness you may long for is already promised in the words your people gave the world.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `Pew Research — Jewish Americans in 2020`, url: `https://www.pewresearch.org/religion/2021/05/11/jewish-americans-in-2020/` },
