	voicesCreditHtml={`Photos via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Wikimedia Commons</a> &mdash; Andrew Murray, George MacDonald, and Martin Luther (all public domain).`}
	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>You may not feel everything the first time you read. That is alright. The nearness of God is not a passing feeling — it is a promise as old as your people, and promises take root quietly. Every verse you take in is a word from the God who has loved Israel from the beginning, planting something that endures.</p><p class="mt-4" style="color: var(--color-ink);">"So shall My word be that goes out from My mouth; it shall not return to Me empty, but shall accomplish that which I purpose." <span style="color: var(--color-muted);">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What your Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>"I have loved you with an everlasting love; with unfailing kindness I have drawn you to Myself. Before the world began I chose your people, and I have not forgotten you for a single day. When you were a child I taught you to walk and lifted you to My cheek.</p><p>I am your Father. I am holy, and I am near. Do not think Me only distant, only Sovereign — I am the One who has compassion on His children, who gathers, who sings over those I love. You are precious in My sight. Come close, and know Me as the Father I have always been to you."</p>`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for the Jewish people`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we come to You with deep respect and gratitude for the Jewish people — the people of the covenant, through whom Your Scriptures came to the world, and to whom You first made Yourself known. We thank You for their faithfulness across the centuries, and we ask Your blessing, Your peace, and Your protection over them in every land.</p><p>You are the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob, the Holy One who is also a Father to His children. We pray that the warmth of Your Fatherhood, already written in Isaiah and the Psalms and the prophets, would be felt close and personal — that those who revere You from afar would know the nearness You promised. Comfort those who grieve, strengthen those who feel distant, and let Your shalom rest on every home.</p><p>Father, let the words of Your own Scriptures speak life and tenderness, and draw every searching heart into the intimacy You have always offered Your people. May the God who sings over His own be known and loved.</p><p>In Jesus' name, amen.</p>`}
