	faqs={[
		{ question: `Does the Hebrew Bible call God Father?`, answer: `Yes. The Fatherhood of God is rooted in the Hebrew Scriptures themselves. Isaiah 63:16 and 64:8 say plainly, "You, O LORD, are our Father." Deuteronomy 32:6 asks, "Is He not your Father, who created you?" Malachi 2:10 says, "Have we not all one Father?" The God of Israel revealed Himself as Father long before the idea reached the wider world. Read these passages free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Is God a Father in the Old Testament and the Tanakh?`, answer: `Very much so. Psalm 103:13 compares God's compassion to a father's compassion for his children. Hosea 11:1 recalls, "When Israel was a child, I loved him." Jeremiah 31:9 declares, "I am a Father to Israel." Psalm 68:5 calls Him "a father to the fatherless." The Tanakh holds God's awesome holiness and His Fatherly tenderness together. You can read all of these free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Does God love His people?`, answer: `The Scriptures of Israel answer yes again and again. "I have loved you with an everlasting love" (Jeremiah 31:3). Zephaniah 3:17 says God rejoices over His people and quiets them with His love. His love is described as everlasting, faithful, and tender — a Father's love for His children. Read these promises free, with audio, in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What are good Bible verses about God's fatherly love?`, answer: `From the Hebrew Scriptures: Isaiah 64:8 ("You are our Father"), Psalm 103:13 (a father's compassion), Hosea 11:1 ("When Israel was a child, I loved him"), Deuteronomy 32:6 ("Is He not your Father?"), Jeremiah 31:9 ("I am a Father to Israel"), Psalm 68:5 ("a father to the fatherless"), and Malachi 2:10 ("Have we not all one Father?"). Read and hear them all free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Is there a free Bible with audio I can read online?`, answer: `Yes. The Father's Heart Bible™ is free to read and listen to online — no account, no purchase, no app. Open fathersheartbible.com/read and read or hear any book, including Isaiah, the Psalms, Hosea, and the prophets. It comes humbly, as something to weigh for yourself.` },
		{ question: `What is the Father's Heart Bible™, and is it respectful of Jewish faith?`, answer: `The Father's Heart Bible™ is a fresh English translation that brings out the Father-heart of God wherever Scripture reveals it — including throughout the Hebrew Scriptures. It does not aim to replace what the Jewish people treasure, nor to demand anything. It simply makes visible the tender Fatherhood your own prophets and psalms already proclaim, offered with deep respect as an invitation to know the God of your fathers more intimately.` },
		{ question: `How can I begin reading the Scriptures and drawing near to God?`, answer: `Start small and start free. Open fathersheartbible.com/read and begin with a Psalm, or with Isaiah, where God is named as Father. Listen to the audio as you read. Our how-to-pray guide and verses-by-topic pages can help you find words for whatever you carry, and let the nearness your Scriptures promise become personal.` },
